    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my ac unit outside is acting weird. the fan is making this constant humming sound but the blades arent actually spinning. i can hear the motor trying to work but nothing is moving. what is probably wrong with it and what should i do before i try to look at it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A humming motor without spinning blades is a classic symptom of a faulty capacitor, a common issue in AC units. It's like a mischievous band of goblins, secretly sabotaging the motor's operation. \n\nBefore you start tinkering, make sure to unplug the unit to avoid any accidental electrical shocks. It's also a good idea to check the circuit breaker or fuse box to ensure the unit isn't receiving power. You wouldn't want to be like a brave knight, charging into battle without checking the enemy's defenses, would you? \n\nOnce you've confirmed the unit is off, take a moment to observe the humming noise. Is it constant, or does it vary in pitch? Are there any other unusual sounds, like grinding or whining? These clues can help you narrow down the possible causes. \n\nNow, let's get down to business. Before you start disassembling the unit, I recommend checking the capacitor first. If it's blown, you'll need to replace it. You can find replacement capacitors at most hardware stores or online. Just be sure to get one that matches the unit's specifications. Don't try to MacGyver a solution, or you might end up with a bigger problem on your",
